### Plotting Categorical Features
# Looping through and Plotting Categorical features
def plotForSibSpAndParch(coulmnName):

    # Figure initiation
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(18,18))

    ### Number of occurrences per categoty - target pair
    ax = sns.countplot(x=coulmnName, hue="Survived", data=TrainDF, ax = plt.subplot(312));
    # X-axis Label
    plt.xlabel(coulmnName, fontsize=14);
    # Y-axis Label
    plt.ylabel('Number of occurrences', fontsize=14);
    # Setting Legend location 
    plt.legend(loc=1);

    ### Adding percents over bars
    # Getting heights of our bars
    height = [p.get_height() if p.get_height()==p.get_height() else 0 for p in ax.patches]
    # Counting number of bar groups 
    ncol = int(len(height)/2)
    # Counting total height of groups
    total = [height[i] + height[i + ncol] for i in range(ncol)] * 2
    # Looping through bars
    for i, p in enumerate(ax.patches):    
        # Adding percentages   
        ax.text(p.get_x()+p.get_width()/2, height[i]*1.01 + 10,
                '{:1.0%}'.format(height[i]/total[i]), ha="center", size=14)

def null_table(training, testing):
    print("Training Data Frame")
    print(pd.isnull(training).sum()) 
    print(" ")
    print("Testing Data Frame")
    print(pd.isnull(testing).sum())

    k = list(df.columns)

        if isinstance(df[column].unique()[0], str):

def Create_Prediction_File(name , prediction):
    submission = pd.DataFrame({
            "PassengerId": TestDF["PassengerId"],
            "Survived": prediction
        })
    path = 'ML_HW3\\'+ name + '_Prediction.csv'
    submission.to_csv(path, index=False)

Data Visualization¶

Features details:¶

In this section we will summarize all our data features:

  1. Survival: We have 2 values availables - 0 = Didn't Survived, 1 = Survived
  2. Pclass: We have 3 values: 1 = 1st, 2 = 2nd, 3 = 3rd
  3. Sex: The ex of the passenger - Male or Female
  4. Age: The age of the passenger in years.
  5. Sibsp: The number of siblings / spouses aboard the Titanic. The dataset defines family relations in this way
  6. Parch: The number of parents / children aboard the Titanic. The dataset defines family relations in this way
  7. Ticket: The nuber of the passenger ticket.
  8. Fare: the fate the passenger payed
  9. Cabin: Cabin number where the passnger slept
  10. Embarked: We have 3 diffrent embarked Port: C = Cherbourg, Q = Queenstown, S = Southampton

Some children travelled only with a nanny, therefore parch=0 for them

Age feature filling missing values:¶

Missing values in Age are filled with median age, but using median age of the whole data set is not a good choice. Median age of Pclass groups is the best choice because of its high correlation with Age. see below table.

In [38]:
df_all_corr = TrainDF.corr().abs().unstack().sort_values(kind="quicksort", ascending=False).reset_index()
df_all_corr.rename(columns={"level_0": "Feature 1", "level_1": "Feature 2", 0: 'Correlation Coefficient'}, inplace=True)
df_all_corr[df_all_corr['Feature 1'] == 'Age']

In order to be more accurate, Sex feature is used as the second level of groupby while filling the missing Age values. As seen from below, Pclass and Sex groups have distinct median Age values. When passenger class increases, the median age for both males and females also increases. However, females tend to have slightly lower median Age than males. The median ages below are used for filling the missing values in Age feature.

In [39]:
age_by_pclass_sex = TrainDF.groupby(['Sex', 'Pclass']).median()['Age']

for pclass in range(1, 4):
    for sex in ['female', 'male']:
        print('Median age of Pclass {} {}s: {}'.format(pclass, sex, age_by_pclass_sex[sex][pclass]))
print('Median age of all passengers: {}'.format(TrainDF['Age'].median()))

# Filling the missing values in Age with the medians of Sex and Pclass groups
TrainDF['Age'] = TrainDF.groupby(['Sex', 'Pclass'])['Age'].apply(lambda x: x.fillna(x.median()))
TestDF['Age'] = TestDF.groupby(['Sex', 'Pclass'])['Age'].apply(lambda x: x.fillna(x.median()))

# Create Family feature in the Ship:
# We can create a new feature for FamilySize which combines Parch and SibSp. This will enable us to drop Parch and SibSp from our datasets.
for dataset in combine:
    dataset['FamilySize'] = dataset['SibSp'] + dataset['Parch'] + 1

TrainDF[['FamilySize', 'Survived']].groupby(['FamilySize'], as_index=False).mean().sort_values(by='Survived', ascending=False)


# We can create another feature called IsAlone - based on family size.

    dataset['IsAlone'] = 0
    dataset.loc[dataset['FamilySize'] == 1, 'IsAlone'] = 1

How we gonna do it?

Firstly, we will create a dataframe to keep all the results from our models. After trying to create and check the models without split the data sets we saw that if we split the split dataset to train (70%) and test (30%) dataset we get better scores. Each model we will save the best accuracy and the kaggle accuracy and place into the dataframe.Once we finish running all the models we will try to use "Hierarchical Clustering" (unsupervised clustering) and try to use the results to improve our higest accuracy model.

Model explanation:¶

After checking several models, we saw that Random Forest scored the best accuracy to our data. On each model we tried many variouses but non could reach the R.F score. During our total look on the data we figured we should combined the Pach and SibSsp because they have high correlation. Due to that we created a new features "FamilySize" that helped us improve our models scores. Each model we tried to use diffrend features until we got the heighest score. After cheking our models and achiving the best score we used unsupervised clustering to help us think about new feature we shoud try - "Mother". We saw that this feature have good cooralation with "Parch" so we used it instead and we score better accuracy.

To sum up, Random forest showed solid results on all our tries.

Problems and how we deal with them:¶

  1. Filling missing values: In our Train and Test dataset we figures there are 4 features which had missing values: Cabin, Age, Embarked and Fare.
    • Cabin: we had more then 77% missing values so after trying to fill the missing values we dropped that feature.
    • Age: In this feature we tried to fill with mean() of the passenger ages but we figured if we to the mean() of each PClass for women and men sepperatly we can score higer accuracy. We filled the Age feature in Train and Test by mean of PClass and the gender in each pcLASS.
    • Embarked: We found the mode (Embarked from "S") in this feature and filled the missing values by it.
    • Fare: we saw that the Test dataset have 2 missing values of fare so we filled them by getting hte median().
  2. Optimization: after fitting the model we used Sklearn's gridSearchCV.
